@module chisel/cli
@lang go
@version 0.1.0
@purpose CLI interface for semantic refactoring — 3 core commands powered by AID + Cartograph
@depends [chisel/resolve, chisel/edit, chisel/patch]

---

@fn main
@purpose Entry point. Parses CLI args, runs refactoring pipeline: resolve → edit → patch.
@sig () -> None
@params
  Global flags:
    --dir: Path to .aidocs/ directory. Default: auto-discover via walk-up.
    --src: Path to source tree. Default: parent of .aidocs/ directory.
    --apply: Actually modify files. Default: dry-run (preview only).
    --backup: Create .bak files before modifying. Only used with --apply.
    --format: Output format for dry-run. One of: unified (default), json, summary.

---

@workflow cli_usage
@purpose How the CLI is invoked for each refactoring operation
@steps
  1. chisel rename <old> <new> — Rename a symbol across the codebase
     Example: chisel rename QueryEngine GraphQueryEngine
     Example: chisel rename HttpClient.Get HttpClient.Fetch
     Example: chisel rename User.email User.emailAddress
  2. chisel move <symbol> <destination-package> — Move a symbol to another package
     Example: chisel move ValidateEmail validation
     Example: chisel move HttpClient pkg/client
  3. chisel propagate <function> <error-type> — Add error return and propagate through callers
     Example: chisel propagate ProcessRequest ValidationError
     Example: chisel propagate SaveDocument error

---

@workflow refactoring_pipeline
@purpose How every refactoring command executes internally
@steps
  1. Parse: CLI args → Intent struct (kind, target, options)
  2. Load: read AID files from --dir, build Cartograph graph
  3. Resolve: query graph for all references to the target symbol → Resolution
  4. Edit: generate text edits from resolved locations → EditSet
  5. Patch: if --apply, modify files; otherwise, output diff for review
  6. AID update: if source edits succeeded and --apply, update AID files to match
@antipatterns
  - Don't skip the resolve phase. Even for "simple" renames, the graph finds references that grep would miss.
  - Don't apply without showing the diff first. If --apply is set, still log the diff to stderr before applying.
  - Don't update AID before source. If source edits fail, AID must remain unchanged.

---

@decision default_safety
@purpose Protect users from unintended changes
@chosen Three safety layers: (1) dry-run by default, (2) diff always shown, (3) --backup available
@rejected Single confirmation prompt (doesn't work for AI agents), no safety (too dangerous)
@rationale AI agents invoke CLI tools programmatically. A "are you sure?" prompt would block the agent. Instead, the default mode is read-only (dry-run), the diff is always visible, and the agent can make an informed decision to pass --apply after reviewing the output. This design works for both human and AI users.

---

@decision output_format
@purpose How refactoring results are displayed
@chosen Unified diff by default. JSON for programmatic consumption. Summary for quick checks.
@rejected Custom tree format (diffs are the universal language of code changes)
@rationale Developers and AI agents both understand unified diffs. Diffs can be piped to `git apply`, reviewed in any editor, or parsed programmatically. JSON output enables AI agents to inspect individual edits before deciding to apply.

---

@antipatterns
  - Don't parse source code with a language-specific parser. Chisel works through AID + Cartograph + grep, not ASTs. Language-agnostic by design.
  - Don't assume all references are in AID. Grep-based fallback catches call sites and references that AID's [src:] didn't capture.
  - Don't buffer the entire source tree. Load files on demand during the edit phase, not upfront.
